Action:
   if (isFavourite())
        {
            labelManager.removeFavourite(getPlan(), getUser());
        }
        else
        {
            labelManager.addFavourite(getPlan(),  getUser());
        }

If this action is triggered twice at the same moment, it will call addFavourite() twice and two :favourite labels will appear in the database.

When you install a JDK on windows, it usually installs a JDK and JRE component to the following paths:
* {{C:\Java\jdk1.6.0_10}}
* {{C:\Java\jre6}}

When Bamboo automatically detects the presence of local JDKs (after having installed a JDK and Bamboo on Windows), Bamboo appears to assign these locally detected JDKs the path to the JRE executables of the JDK installation (for example, {{C:\Java\jre6}}), rather than the path to the JDK executables instead (i.e. {{C:\Java\jdk1.6.0_10}}).

I'm not sure if this happens on other operating systems.

See https://jira.bamboo.atlassian.com/browse/JIRAFUNCBRA-JDK15-1696

